    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{4r}{r+1}+\frac{r}{r-1}-5} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{3r-5}{\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-1\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{4r}{r+1}+\frac{r}{r-1}-5} 
      \amp = {\frac{4r}{r+1}} \cdot \frac{(r-1)}{(r-1)} + {\frac{r}{r-1}} \cdot \frac{(r+1)}{(r+1)} - \frac{5}{1} \cdot \frac{(r+1)(r-1)}{(r+1)(r-1)} \\
      \amp = \frac{4r(r-1)}{(r+1)(r-1)}  + \frac{r(r+1)}{(r+1)(r-1)} - \frac{5(r+1)(r-1)}{(r+1)(r-1)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{4r(r-1)+r(r+1)-5(r+1)(r-1)}{(r+1)(r-1)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{4r^{2}-4r+r^{2}+1r-5(r^{2}-1)}{(r+1)(r-1)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{4r^{2}-4r+r^{2}+1r-5r^{2}+5}{(r+1)(r-1)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{-3r+5}{\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-1\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Notice that <m>{-\frac{3r-5}{\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-1\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}</m> is also correct. We should actually factor whenever possible, in case we can reduce the rational expression.</p>
</solution>
